1918. These two sections are followed by a collection of kanikau or lamentations, interviews with Kalaupapa residents, and a list of Hawaiian language newspapers. Introductory paragraphs for groupings of newspaper articles assist the reader in visualizing the physical landscape and understanding the history and significance of a particular location. The poetry of the Hawaiian language is evident throughout the translations, especially in the kanikau.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLeprosyxPatientszHawaiizKalaupapaxSocial conditions. 7aREFERENCE / Research.2bisacsh1 aEllinwood, Iāsona K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeSmith, Keao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z978311071955008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311065811840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082487330140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824873301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824873301/original  a978-3-11-065811-8  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-071955-0  DG Plus eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles